The default wiki content has e.g.:

bq. Go ahead and try:

$ git clone https://bitbucket.org/jean/pools.git/wiki


This fails:

{code}
#!bash

jean@klippie:~/repos/git$ git clone https://bitbucket.org/jean/pools.git/wiki pools-wiki
Initialized empty Git repository in /home/jean/repos/git/pools-wiki/.git/
error: The requested URL returned error: 401 while accessing https://bitbucket.org/jean/pools.git/wiki/info/refs

{code}

This works:

{code}
#!bash

jean@klippie:~/repos/git$ git clone ssh://git@bitbucket.org/jean/pools.git/wiki pools-wiki
[...]
Receiving objects: 100% (3/3), done.

{code}

Using the Creole syntax in a wiki to link to a page not in the wiki produces a bad result. For example, the following Creole syntax:

{code}
#!Creole

[[http://www.creeds.net/Heidelberg/hdlb44.htm|catechism]]
{code}

produces the following broken HTML:

{code}
#!HTML

<a href="<a href="http://www.creeds.net/Heidelberg/hdlb44.htm" rel="nofollow"  >http://www.creeds.net/Heidelberg/hdlb44.htm</a>">catechism</a>
{code}

"Need help?" block on the main page (when user is logged in) has something like broken vertical spacing.

It can be fixed by following css code:

{code}
:::css
.help-link.api {
  margin-top: 20px;
}
{code}

Reproducible with:

bc. [\\
{\\
"regex": "<pattern>",\\
"action": "<action>"[,\\
"<argument>": "<value>"[, ...]\\
]\\
}[, ...]\\
]

I was able to accept an invitation to a repo from a different email address. The process is as follows:

* I was logged into my bitbucket account under &#x27;abc@gmail.com&#x27;
* I received an invitation to a bitbucket repo under my work email &#x27;xyz@work.net&#x27;
* While still logged into bitbucket under &#x27;abc@gmail.com&#x27; account, I clicked on the invitation sent to &#x27;xyz@work.net&#x27;, I now have the repo under &#x27;abc@gmail.com&#x27; account.

Not sure if this is intended.
